After calculating the MCdb, the moisture ratio (MR) of the samples was calculated as it allows comparing the different samples with each other by normalising the moisture contents with their initial moisture contents and thereby displaying them as values between one and zero. MR for the carrots was calculated using Eq. 7 and Eq. 87MR=MCdb,1−MCeMCdb,0−MCe\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ MR=\frac{MC_{db,1}-{MC}_e}{MC_{\mathrm{d}b,0}-{MC}_e} $$\end{document}

where MCdb, 1 is the dry basis MC at a given time, MCdb, 0 is the dry basis MC before drying and MCe is the equilibrium moisture content. As the influence of MCe is relatively small (≤ 2%) (Diamante and Munro (1993), the MR equation was further simplified to Eq. 88MR=MCdb,1MCdb,0\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ MR=\frac{MC_{db,1}}{MC_{db,0}} $$\end{document}

The MR obtained from Eq. 8 was then used to build a model for drying behaviour for carrots. Modelling allows the prediction of drying behaviour at a given time throughout the process and thus the development of process control strategies for a product. As three different strategies were implemented within this study, it was important to evaluate the possibility of one model being fit for the different data sets. For this purpose, three of the most well-known models for thin layer drying of food products particularly Newton, Page and the Henderson & Pabis model (Agrawal & Singh, 1977; Ayensu, 1997; Henderson & Pabis, 1961) were used to fit the drying curves. They are represented by Eqs. 9, 10 and 11.
